American-style crony capitalism
Do you remember the Asian financial crisis? When the American Ministry of Finance and its IMF allies blamed the problems of this region on crony capitalism, lack of transparency, and an ineffective government?
Countries were encouraged to follow the American model, to use American accounting firms, and to introduce American entrepreneurs to teach them how to run their businesses.
Irrespective of the fact that under the leadership of its own entrepreneurs, East Asia has developed more rapidly than any other region—and with greater stability—for the past three decades.
The growing Enron scandal lends new meaning to two well-known American proverbs: "You reap what you sow" and "A pot calling the kettle black".
Enron used large accounting schemes and complicated financial instruments (derivatives) to mislead investors about its true value.
No transparency here.
It used its money to gain influence and power, shaping US energy policy and avoiding regulations.
This kind of favoritism capitalism is not new, nor is it the domain of one political party.
Former US Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin allegedly tried to influence the current government to intervene on Enron's behalf in the controversial Indian conflict.
When he was on duty, he intervened when the supposedly independent accounting standards definition office attempted to clean up the accounts of the senior executives' bonuses.
This partly explains why efforts to make corporate accounting more transparent were impeded.
The enthusiasm of America to inject several billion dollars into airlines or to create cartels to protect its steel and aluminum industries suggests that the ideology of free market is just a thin veil for the well-being of old industries: giving favors to those who have the right connections.
For some, the fact that Enron was not bailed out and that the problems were not revealed is evidence of the lack of crony capitalism.
My interpretation is different: it attests to the importance of a free press that may not stop abuses but can reduce them.
When the press began to investigate Enron, the number of Congressional members who had accepted money from Enron was disclosed.
Campaign contributions were not simply a matter of public interest but an investment.
Like most of Enron's investments, everything seemed to work out fine in the short term but did not yield results in the long term.
Several lessons can be drawn from this company.
Some pertain to politics: the Enron scandal reinforces the argument for campaign finance reform and the need for even more effective laws that must be disclosed to the public.
The democracies are undermined by business interests that in fact can buy elections.
However, the Bush administration refuses to disclose information that would attest to the role of business interests in defining its energy policy.
Other lessons pertain to the economy, more particularly to the economics of information.
For markets to function, for the appropriate signals aimed at efficiently allocating resources to be provided, investors must receive as much information as possible.
There are inherent conflicts of interest: owners and managers are naturally motivated to present the rosiest picture possible.
The control of accounts is intended to place limits on potential abuses.
But who will guard the guardians?
Who will control the controllers of accounts?
We count greatly on motivation.
Auditors wish to maintain their reputation.
But the relationship between advisory and accounting control practices brings about other distorted incentives: a motive to please clients who do not appreciate unfavorable reports.
Arthur Levitt, the former chairman of the Securities and Exchange Commission, recognized the conflict: given that many within the accounting firms focus on their own short-term interests, the integrity of controls could be compromised.
He is likely the unrecognized hero of the debacle.
But accounting firms and their corporate clients – given how the cabal has developed – vigorously attacked his proposal to separate advisory and accounting control activities.
What Levitt understood – and what Enron's collapse so clearly demonstrated – is that while motivations are important, unfettered markets cannot provide the best motivations on their own.
The markets cannot provide incentives for the creation of wealth; they can only provide incentives for the types of schemes that Enron implemented.
The new economy—and its complex financial instruments—highlights the problems of reliable accounting control structures; it makes them easier to complicate.
Rather than confronting these issues, corporate America systematically turns away from them, supported and encouraged by American favoritism capitalism.
The major problem of our time is to find the right balance between government and the market.
The status quo will assert that Enron was an exception: that its disappearance was due to fraud, that we have laws against fraud, and that those who violate these laws must face the consequences and will do so.
But the vast majority of Enron's actions were legal.
Its accountants state that its central practices complied with the law and that thousands of companies act in the same way.
They are right—and that is precisely the problem.
Investors need to be assured that the information they receive reflects the company's economic situation sufficiently.
Within the current regulatory and legal framework, with derivatives and other off-balance-sheet liabilities, investors have no means to receive these guarantees at present.
We need better standards and more effective laws.
Though we will never be able to prevent all abuses, we can check motivations.
We can try to instill better ethical standards.
But we cannot rely on them when so many people in the world find nothing wrong with the phenomenon of the "revolving door."
They claim to manage conflicts of interest, but we observe that they manage them for their own interests.
But even when evidence of this type of abuse becomes evident, new places for abuse are repeatedly created - consider the repeal of the Glass Steagall Act in the United States, which separated commercial from investment banking.
We have repeatedly witnessed the consequences of the excesses of unregulated market liberalization.
We must now resist the temptation to lean towards the other extreme.
The challenge is to achieve the right balance.
